  "output": "This is a Python job-scraping CLI (async fetchers → SQLite dedup store → notifiers), not a web app — there's no React/frontend code, so that section doesn't apply here. I found real issues in the other four categories. 132 sources are configured (`sources.yaml`), many paginating up to 400+ roles each, and this runs on a 12h schedule (per recent commit history), so per-run overhead compounds over time.\n\n## 1. N+1 query pattern — `store.py:55-74` (`Store.diff`)\n\nFor every job returned by a run (can be thousands across 132 sources), `diff()` does a separate `SELECT` and then a separate `INSERT`/`UPDATE` — one round trip per job, all inside a Python loop:\n\n```python\nfor job in jobs:\n    row = cur.execute(\"SELECT content_hash FROM jobs WHERE key = ?\", (job.key,)).fetchone()\n    if row is None:\n        ...\n        self._insert(cur, job, now)\n    else:\n        if row[\"content_hash\"] != job.content_hash:\n            ...\n            self._update(cur, job, now)\n        else:\n            cur.execute(\"UPDATE jobs SET last_seen=? WHERE key=?\", (now, job.key))\n```\n\nSince SQLite is embedded, there's no network latency per call, but each call still pays Python/SQLite statement-prepare overhead, and it scales linearly with total jobs fetched (thousands/run × 2×/day). Fix: load all existing hashes in one query, diff in memory, and batch the writes with `executemany`:\n\n```python\ndef diff(self, jobs: list[Job]) -> tuple[list[Job], list[Job]]:\n    now = datetime.now(timezone.utc).isoformat(timespec=\"seconds\")\n    existing = {r[\"key\"]: r[\"content_hash\"]\n                for r in self.conn.execute(\"SELECT key, content_hash FROM jobs\")}\n\n    new, changed, touched = [], [], []\n    insert_rows, update_rows = [], []\n    for job in jobs:\n        h = existing.get(job.key)\n        row = {**job.to_row(), \"now\": now}\n        if h is None:\n            new.append(job); insert_rows.append(row)\n        elif h != row[\"content_hash\"]:\n            changed.append(job); update_rows.append(row)\n        else:\n            touched.append((now, job.key))\n\n    cur = self.conn.cursor()\n    if insert_rows:\n        cur.executemany(\"\"\"INSERT INTO jobs (key, source, company, external_id, title,\n            url, location, department, employment_type, posted_at, salary_range,\n            content_hash, first_seen, last_seen)\n            VALUES (:key,:source,:company,:external_id,:title,:url,:location,\n            :department,:employment_type,:posted_at,:salary_range,:content_hash,:now,:now)\"\"\",\n            insert_rows)\n    if update_rows:\n        cur.executemany(\"\"\"UPDATE jobs SET title=:title, url=:url, location=:location,\n            department=:department, employment_type=:employment_type,\n            posted_at=:posted_at, salary_range=:salary_range,\n            content_hash=:content_hash, last_seen=:now WHERE key=:key\"\"\",\n            update_rows)\n    if touched:\n        cur.executemany(\"UPDATE jobs SET last_seen=? WHERE key=?\", touched)\n    self.conn.commit()\n    return new, changed\n```\n\nOne `SELECT`, three batched `executemany` calls instead of up to 3N round trips.\n\n## 2. Redundant computation — `filters.py:11-27` (`match`/`_compile`)\n\n`filter_jobs` calls `match()` once per fetched job, and `match()` recompiles the include/exclude regex list on **every call**:\n\n```python\ndef match(job, *, include=None, exclude=None, ...):\n    if exclude:\n        if any(p.search(haystack) for p in _compile(exclude)):   # recompiled per job\n    if include:\n        if not any(p.search(haystack) for p in _compile(include)):  # recompiled per job\n```\n\nPython's `re` module does cache compiled patterns internally, so this isn't full re-compilation cost every time, but it's still a dict lookup + list rebuild per keyword per job, and that cache (default 512 entries) can be evicted if the process compiles a lot of other patterns (it does — Apple/Google/D.E. Shaw/Two Sigma parsers all compile regexes during the same run). Hoist it once, outside the loop:\n\n```python\ndef filter_jobs(jobs: list[Job], rules: dict) -> list[Job]:\n    cutoff = None\n    max_age = rules.get(\"max_age_days\")\n    if max_age:\n        cutoff = datetime.now(timezone.utc) - timedelta(days=float(max_age))\n    include = _compile(rules.get(\"include_keywords\") or [])\n    exclude = _compile(rules.get(\"exclude_keywords\") or [])\n    locations = rules.get(\"locations\")\n    return [j for j in jobs if match(j, include=include, exclude=exclude,\n                                      locations=locations, cutoff=cutoff)]\n```\n\nand change `match()` to accept already-compiled patterns (drop the `_compile()` calls inside it).\n\n## 3. Caching opportunities\n\n- **SQLite write-ahead logging**: `Store.__init__` (`store.py:36-41`) never sets `PRAGMA journal_mode=WAL`. The `next_seq` docstring explicitly mentions \"parallel pipeline workers\" using `BEGIN IMMEDIATE` — under the default rollback-journal mode, concurrent workers will block each other on every write far more than under WAL. One-line fix: `self.conn.execute(\"PRAGMA journal_mode=WAL\")` after connecting.\n- **No conditional/cached HTTP fetches**: every run refetches full boards from scratch (`fetchers.py`), even though most postings are unchanged run-to-run — that's inherent to how these ATS APIs work (most don't expose `ETag`/`Last-Modified`), so this is a soft suggestion rather than a bug: worth checking whether any of the JSON APIs (Greenhouse, Lever, Ashby) return conditional-request headers you could pass `If-None-Match` against to shortcut a 304 instead of paying full page-by-page pagination every 12h.\n- **`content_hash` recomputed**: it's a `@property` on `Job` (`models.py:66-69`) doing a SHA-256 hash of a joined string. It gets computed twice for changed rows — once in the (proposed) `diff()` comparison, once inside `to_row()`. Cheap in isolation, but since `Job` is a `slots=True` dataclass you can't just bolt on `functools.cached_property`; if you want to avoid the double hash, compute it once via `row = job.to_row()` and read `row[\"content_hash\"]` for the comparison instead of `job.content_hash` separately. Low priority — SHA-256 over a short string is microseconds.\n\n## 4. Memory\n\nThis is a short-lived CLI process (`asyncio.run(...)` then exit), not a server, so there's no classic *leak* — `Store` and `httpx.AsyncClient` are both cleaned up via context managers/`finally` (`pipeline.py:42`, `fetchers.py:1142-1146`). One real footprint issue instead:\n\n- **`Job.raw` retained for the whole run** (`models.py:52`): every parsed job keeps the full source JSON payload in `raw` (`field(default_factory=dict)`), used only for debugging/future fields. `to_row()` drops it before it ever reaches SQLite (`d.pop(\"raw\", None)`, `store.py`/`models.py:73`), so it's pure peak-RSS overhead across fetch → filter → diff. Across large boards (Apple ~6,400 roles, Amazon/Microsoft/Google in the thousands, times whatever fraction of your 132 sources hit those `max_pages` caps) that's a lot of retained dict garbage held simultaneously in `fetch_all`'s gathered results. If a single run is peaking on memory, dropping `raw` right after parsing (or making it opt-in per source) is the lever to pull.\n\n## Priority\n\n1. Batch `Store.diff()` (#1) — biggest, clearest win, scales with total jobs/run.\n2. Hoist regex compilation in `filters.py` (#2) — trivial fix, same order-of-magnitude win.\n3. `PRAGMA journal_mode=WAL` — one line, directly addresses the concurrent-worker contention the codebase already anticipates.\n4. `raw` payload retention — only matters if you're seeing actual memory pressure on the big boards; otherwise skip.\n\nWant me to apply the `store.py` and `filters.py` fixes now?\n",
